<TEXT>
the ronald reagan presidential library is 
nearing completion on a california hilltop but it may be years 
before the former presidents papers are available to scholars 
reagan is the first president to come under a 1978 law that 
makes presidential papers the property of the government and gives 
the national archives five years to process them 
we would prefer to use the full five years for processing 
john t fawcett assistant archivist for presidential libraries 
said in an interview 
however some papers may be available before the expiration of 
the five years which would be jan 20 1994 fawcett said the law 
also requires the agency to make such records available to the 
public as rapidly and completely as possible 
most former presidents tend to want to open these papers 
rather quickly the archives official said there are good 
administrative reasons why we should wait five years to begin 
opening the papers but we may do it sooner 
cathy goldberg a spokeswoman for reagan said from los angeles 
that reagan is pleased that scholars students and the public 
will have access to the presidential papers of his administration 
but since the library is under construction at this time the date 
of availability has not been determined 
samuel gammon executive director of the american historical 
association said in general we are always anxious to see 
things as soon as possible but we do recognize that the national 
archives in handling presidential libraries has certain financial 
problems and so on 
until reagan former presidents owned their white house papers 
except for those of richard nixon which were made government 
property b special legislation after the watergate scandals since 
the establishment of the presidential library system beginning 
with the franklin d roosevelt library in hyde park ny other 
presidents have donated their papers to the government and they 
have generally been available in less than five years 
reagans library being built near simi valley calif is 
expected to be completed shortly after his 80th birthday on feb 6 
after that the archives will begin moving in the papers which are 
now stored in a warehouse in culver city calif then the ronald 
reagan foundation will install museum exhibits dealing with the 
careers of reagan and his wife nancy dedication of the library is 
scheduled for early november 
reagan the first president to serve eight years since dwight d 
eisenhower in the 1950s left behind a record amount of paper an 
estimated 52600 cubic feet fawcett said more than 20000 cubic 
feet or 40 million pages almost equal to the entire bulk of the 
nixon papers were destroyed in a program initiated by the 
archives these papers were part of the mail to the president from 
members of the public fawcett said a sample was kept along with 
careful records of the rest these were the only reagan papers 
destroyed he said 
the documents had to be transported farther than any other 
presidential papers had since reagan is from california so for 
the first time the papers were flown fawcett said the archives 
considered using trucks or trains or even barging the documents 
through the panama canal but concluded that flying them would cost 
about the same as truck transportation and be safer and quicker 
a staff of 14 has been processing the papers at culver city the 
library will have a staff of 22 
under the law the former presidents personal papers those not 
related to official business remain his own property this 
category includes papers dealing with his 1984 reelection 
campaign but fawcett said reagan like jimmy carter before him 
has decided to deed campaign papers to the government 
both reagan and then vice president george bush exercised an 
option in the law to shield several categories of papers from 
public scrutiny for up to 12 years these include classified 
national security matters information about appointments to 
federal offices trade secrets confidential advice of presidential 
advisers information infringing on personal privacy and 
information that is protected by other laws 
archives is deciding what papers fit into each category if a 
researcher challenges such a classification archives must justify 
its decision within 30 days 
fawcett said archivists will make recommendations to reagans 
representative los angeles attorney stephen blitz to open up some 
of these papers in less than 12 years for instance he said there 
may often be no longer any reason to keep advice to the president 
on past decisions confidential 
blitz office said he was out of town and not available 
bushs vice presidential papers are stored at the archives in 
washington and may become part of his presidential library fawcett 
said rice university in houston the university of houston and 
texas a amp m have all bid to be the site of that library 
however long it takes for reagans papers to become public it 
is certain to be sooner than before the advent of presidential 
libraries 
abraham lincolns papers were not open to public research until 
1949 and the adams family still imposes some restrictions on the 
papers of john and john quincy adams fawcett said 
</TEXT>
