<TEXT>
next year in the philippines probably 
will be a grim one of rising inflation a declining economy and 
political instability 
after three years of economic growth rates over 5 percent many 
economists predict recession in 1991 with sharp increases in 
unemployment especially if war breaks out in the persian gulf 
higher oil costs that followed iraqs seizure of kuwait on aug 
2 forced the government to raise consumer fuel prices by more than 
45 percent 
that sent shock waves through an economy already struggling with 
doubledigit inflation and there are clear signs the business 
community is losing confidence in president corazon aquino 
the philippines gets 64 percent of its energy from imported oil 
and more than 80 percent of it comes from the middle east 
new foreign investments declined by 47 percent in the first 
eight months of 1990 and the departure of capital rose 342 percent 
as financiers moved their money to more stable havens 
we have not only lost our sense of bearings we have taken 
leave of our senses teodoro benigno mrs aquinos former 
spokesman wrote in the philippine star the philippines is now 
looked upon abroad as a basket case 
annual inflation of about 12 percent is expected to reach 16 
percent even without war in the gulf that will lead to demands by 
labor for wage increases industry says it cannot afford 
strikes and demonstrations are going to abound in the months 
ahead political and economic risk consultancy ltd of hong kong 
said in a report last month the government is widely perceived 
as being helpless 
aurelio periquet president of the philippine chamber of 
commerce and industry said industrial output could decline 40 
percent in 1991 because of higher fuel costs and a chronic energy 
shortage 
labor secretary ruben torres said recently that unemployment in 
this nation of 60 million people may rise to 13 percent from the 
current level of 9 percent 
thousands of filipinos have fled jobs in iraq and kuwait not 
only adding to the unemployment rolls but reducing remittances a 
major source of hard currency 
a national election scheduled for 1992 with no clear successor 
to mrs aquino in sight virtually guarantees political 
uncertainty the president has said she will not seek a second 
term 
mutinous soldiers after seven uprisings against mrs aquino 
say they will try at least once more to overthrow her communist 
rebels remain active but their strength has declined because of 
ideological differences and failures in strategy 
mrs aquino says her governments economic strategy was derailed 
by the persian gulf and an earthquake in july that killed nearly 
1700 people critics blame the looming economic crisis on 
government indecision and mismanagement 
fearful of domestic unrest the aquino government stalled for 
nearly 18 months on a pledge to the international monetary fund to 
reduce the budget deficit by eliminating subsidies on prices of 
petroleum products 
the deficit grew to 60 billion pesos 21 billion more than 
three times the original estimate causing the imf to delay new 
loans and aid 
on dec 5 the government raised fuel prices 45 percent more 
than the increase for crude oil that plunged mrs aquinos 
administration into a political crisis marked by nationwide 
transport strikes and calls for her resignation 
foreign exchange has become so scarce industrialist raul 
concepcion declared in a recent speech that even if oil fell to 
20 a barrel the philippines still would not have the dollars to 
pay 
our exports at 8 billion will be flat he said people 
do not seem to be aware of the gravity of the crisis and the 
government seems reluctant to open up 
despite the problems the public appears tired of politics after 
years of political upheaval 
demonstrations against oil price increases have been minuscule 
compared with the people power uprising of 1986 that drove the 
late president ferdinand marcos into exile and propelled mrs 
aquino to power 
jose luis alcuaz a former government telecommunications chief 
who organized recent protests of oil prices said people have been 
numbed by a series of problems its really difficult to organize 
now it will take some time 
that may explain in part why no clear successor to mrs aquino 
has emerged national elections are scheduled for may 1992 
among possible candidates mentioned are house speaker ramon 
mitra defense secretary fidel ramos senate president jovito 
salonga businessman eduardo cojuangco and former the former 
immigration chief miriam defensorsantiago 
none seems to have generated public enthusiasm 
many filipinos believe the structure mrs aquino set up early in 
her administration is too unwieldy to work regardless of who is 
president 
in 1986 she reestablished a usstyle bicameral legislature 
and presided over the writing of a new constitution modeled after 
the american system of checks and balances 
without strong executive leadership the system proved sluggish 
and decisions come only after long painful processes of 
compromise 
</TEXT>
