<TEXT>
a friendly 24year alliance between the 
national endowment for the arts and new york theater producer 
joseph papp collapsed in bitter enmity last month after an 
acrimonious exchange of letters over the issue of obscenity in the 
arts 
at the end papp had spurned nearly 748000 in federal grants 
and accused nea chairman john e frohnmayer of betraying the arts 
community in a futile attempt to appease the fanatical zeal of 
the religious right 
frohnmayer accused papp of inexcusable and selfserving 
behavior in rejecting the nea grants to protest a congressional ban 
on federal support for arts projects that might be deemed obscene 
papp president of the new york shakespeare festival fired his 
parting shot in a nov 15 letter asking how frohnmayer intended to 
implement new legislation which dropped the obscenity ban but 
requires the nea to consider general standards of decency in 
its grantmaking decisions 
your past record provides little assurance of an arts 
atmosphere free of subtle and notsosubtle intimidation papp 
wrote 
copies of the private sevenmonth exchange of letters between 
papp and frohnmayer were released by nea headquarters in response 
to a freedom of information act request by the associated press 
in separate interviews thursday frohnmayer and papp made clear 
that neither was in a hurry to heal their breach 
if we can restore relations with saddam hussein anything is 
possible papp said in a telephone interview from new york 
i suspect theyll come back at some point frohnmayer said 
but i dont propose to do anything about it myself 
papps battle with the nea under frohnmayers leadership 
coincides with serious financial problems at the new york 
shakespeare festival which papp founded in 1954 in a church 
basement on the lower east side 
the nonprofit theater organization largest in the united 
states now includes the fivestage public theater in manhattan 
free shakespeare performances at the delacorte theater in central 
park an annual latin festival and numerous other theatrical 
ventures 
papp received his first federal grant totaling 100000 in 
1966 a year after the arts endowment was created by congress 
earlier this month papp announced the festival will lay off 30 
of its 123 employees at the end of the year to save about 750000 
a year just about the amount of nea money he had turned away 
its totally a matter of economics papp said 
the producers battle with frohnmayer was fought over 
antiobscenity legislation which congress passed in october 1989 at 
the behest of sen jesse helms rnc the nea chairman has final 
authority to decide whether grants are approved or rejected under 
the law 
papp also objected to frohnmayers requirement that grant 
recipients sign an antiobscenity pledge even though it wasnt 
required under the law the nea chairman rescinded the pledge after 
congress repealed the obscenity ban last october and substituted 
the decency standard 
relations between the two men began to sour when papp wrote 
frohnmayer on april 9 expressing dismay about the obscenity ban and 
misgivings about the unthinkable if not downright subversive 
act of accepting a 50000 endowment grant under those conditions 
papp rejected the 50000 
the mood of the correspondence changed drastically after 
frohnmayer in late june overruled an nea panel of outside judges 
and rejected grants to four controversial performance artists 
whose solo stage acts usually deal with gay and lesbian issues 
racism and politics 
in a fourpage singlespaced letter dated july 3 papp charged 
that frohnmayer had sadly become jesse helms enforcer a censor 
a role illbefitting the leader of the arts in america by denying 
the four grants 
you must realize dear john that no matter how far you go 
you will never be able to appease the fanatical zeal of the 
religious right papp wrote 
papp urged frohnmayer to reverse himself and approve the four 
grants even if it meant possibly being fired by president bush 
do you want praise from senator helms and his cohorts or to 
live by your conscience and to be revered by americans who believe 
in the arts as a crucial part of our democracy papp asked 
frohnmayer didnt write back this time 
instead he rejected the appeals of the four grant applications 
karen finley holly hughes john fleck and tim miller they sued 
frohnmayer in federal court charging that he violated the 
constitution by denying the funds for political rather than 
artistic reasons 
on nov 1 after congress imposed the decency standard on 
arts endowment grants papp sent frohnmayer a curt threeparagraph 
letter 
he wrote that unreasonable restrictive measures make it 
impossible for the new york shakespeare festival to continue its 
relationship with the national endowment for the arts 
accordingly papp said he rejected as unacceptable nea 
grants totaling 323000 which had been approved the previous may 
and july 
because papp never claimed the funds before the fiscal year 
ended sept 30 the undisbursed grant money automatically reverted 
to the us treasury 
frohnmayer was outraged 
you sat on those grants throughout the duration of the fiscal 
year and now tell us that you will not use them thus denying 
323000 to some other deserving arts applicant he wrote papp on 
nov 5 
your actions are inexcusable and selfserving he added 
frohnmayer served notice he would withdraw three other papp 
grant applications from consideration unless he heard from the new 
york producer by nov 16 
in a nov 15 letter the last of the exchange papp confirmed 
he was withdrawing the three applications for new grants totaling 
375000 that brought to 748000 the federal funds awarded or 
applied for that papp rejected 
