<TEXT>
the sponge fishermen of biscayne bay are feeling a 
squeeze on their livelihoods a state proposal in its final drafts 
would ban sponge fishing in biscayne national park covering about 
twothirds of the spongefertile biscayne bay 
federal and state officials worry that continued removal of 
sponges would seriously threaten the bays fragile ecosystem 
the fishermen insist their activity doesnt hurt the bays 
environment also threatened by shore development and heavy 
recreational use and keeps them and their families alive 
i dont know what im going to do said 77yearold pedro 
chico cordova a cuban immigrant who fishes with his son in 
biscayne bay ive been doing this all my life theres nothing i 
can do except for this 
sponge fishermen have worked biscayne bay which stretches about 
50 miles from key largo to north miami for nearly 1 centuries 
the fishing continued even after the southern end south from key 
biscayne was declared a national park in 1980 
a blight in the mediterranean in 1987 destroyed most of the 
mediterranean sponge population and forced a drastic increase in 
prices worldwide the natural sponges are considered superior to 
manmade sponges in some types of cleaning and cosmetic 
applications 
with the price increase the industry exploded at the prime 
florida sponge fishing sites in biscayne bay tarpon springs and 
the florida keys by 1989 as many as 30 boats with three or four 
men each were pulling sponges from the bay 
the mediterranean stock has since revived and the number of 
sponge fishermen in the bay has dropped to about 40 
thats still too many for park rangers 
its in excess of what the bay can handle said richard 
curry resource management coordinator for biscayne national park 
park officials say sponges are an irreplaceable component of a 
delicate marine ecosystem they act as water filters and their 
porous bodies provide habitats for smaller organisms such as 
juvenile fish and crabs 
further commercial fishing is contrary to the mandate of the 
national park service the officials say 
were here to preserve and protect the resources not preserve 
and utilize the resources said curry whos studied the bays 
ecosystem for 13 years 
responding to the park services concern the state fisheries 
commission recently passed the proposal to ban sponge fishing in 
the park it will hold a public hearing on jan 8 and fine tune the 
plan by its meeting at the end of january 
the present version of the plan calls for a gradual phaseout of 
sponge fishing in the park over the next year fishermen will be 
able to spend only two out of every four weeks on the water until 
dec 1 1991 when the commercial fishing of sponges will be 
prohibited entirely 
curry says the sponge ban may presage a wider ban on other 
commercial fisheries in the bay 
the fisheries commission estimated that fishermen harvested more 
than 1600 pounds of sponges last year 
some use environmentally harmful methods of fishing curry said 
they spread cooking oil on the surface of the water for better 
visibility and in violation of the law spend more than the 14 
days on the water in boats with poor sanitary facilities curry 
said 
in addition officials say sponges are being removed much 
faster than they can grow back 
the pure numbers of fishermen indicated to us that the 
harvesting was in excess of what the bay could handle said james 
a sanders park superintendent 
the fishermen all cuban immigrants are bitter about the 
proposed ban and perceive it as a personal attack on their way of 
life 
the workers are going to sue the government because you just 
cant throw the fishermen out on the street said cordova who 
grew up in the sponge fishing town of caibarien cuba 
</TEXT>
